  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The $25 visa fee creates a false impression of affordability. The Bahamas is one of the most expensive places in the Caribbean. Plan for $3,000-5,000/month minimum.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skimping on Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Limited healthcare facilities mean you may need evacuation to Florida for serious conditions. Don't cheap out on evacuation coverage—it could cost $50,000+ out of pocket.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Reliable Internet Everywhere</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Nassau has decent internet, but Out Islands can be spotty. If internet is critical, verify connectivity before committing to a location.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Planning for Hurricanes</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Hurricane season (June-November) is real. Have evacuation plans, understand your insurance coverage for weather events, and consider timing your stay.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting About Groceries</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Almost everything is imported. A grocery run that costs $100 in the US costs $200-300 in Bahamas. Factor this into your budget.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Bahamas -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in the Bahamas</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare in the Bahamas is adequate in Nassau but limited elsewhere. Many expats fly to Florida for anything beyond basic care.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Facilities</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Princess Margaret Hospital</strong> - Nassau, public hospital, largest in country</li>
      <li><strong>Doctors Hospital</strong> - Nassau, private, better for expats</li>
      <li><strong>Walk-In Clinics</strong> - Nassau, various locations for minor issues</li>
      <li><strong>Out Island Clinics</strong> - Basic care only, evacuation for serious cases</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Private, Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> $75-150</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $150-300</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency room:</strong> $300-800</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital stay:</strong> $1,000+/day</li>
      <li><strong>Medical evacuation to Miami:</strong> $15,000-50,000</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>Florida option:</strong> Many Bahamians and expats fly to Miami for specialists, surgeries, and complex care. It's a 50-minute flight and often better value with US insurance networks.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is the visa only $25?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Bahamas launched BEATS during COVID to attract remote workers and boost the economy. The low fee was intentional to make it accessible. They profit from your spending in-country, not from visa fees.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there really no income tax?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Correct. The Bahamas has no personal income tax, no capital gains tax, and no wealth tax. Government revenue comes from import duties, VAT (12%), and tourism. Your remote work income is tax-free.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Where should I live?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Nassau (New Providence) has the most amenities, best internet, and healthcare. Paradise Island is touristy but nice. The Out Islands (Exumas, Eleuthera, Harbour Island) offer escape but fewer services. Most nomads start in Nassau.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How's the internet?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Nassau has reasonable internet (50-100 Mbps available). The Out Islands have more limited and less reliable connectivity. Always verify before committing to a location if internet is critical.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I renew the BEATS visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, the BEATS visa is renewable annually for $25. There's no stated limit on renewals, making long-term stays possible if you continue to meet the requirements.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about hurricanes?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Hurricane season runs June through November. The Bahamas is in the hurricane belt. Have evacuation plans, understand your insurance coverage, and consider travel timing. Many nomads leave during peak hurricane months (August-October).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
